      <hedline>
        <hl1>Oil's Dual Threat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Paul R Epstein (Center for Health and Global Environment) says ferocious winds and oil spill that devastated France in December are both due to global reliance on fossil fuels</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Jan. 22 Le Croisic Journal captures the dual tragedies afflicting France. Ferocious winds in December compounded the damage from an oil spill, and fossil fuels underlie both assaults.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Jan. 22 Le Croisic Journal captures the dual tragedies afflicting France. Ferocious winds in December compounded the damage from an oil spill, and fossil fuels underlie both assaults.</p>
        <p>North Atlantic warming has melted Arctic Sea ice, sending a cold tongue and frigid winds across North America and Europe. Meanwhile, cold Pacific upwelling from La Nina is part of a multi-decade correction.</p>
        <p>Our climate shows signs of instability, and wide swings are projected if we keep polluting the air. But it is the full cycle of fossil fuels -- extraction, mining, refining, transport and combustion of oil and coal -- that harms our health, ecosystems and economies.</p>
        <p>PAUL R. EPSTEIN, M.D.  Boston, Jan. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is associate director, the Center for Health and the Global Environment, Harvard Medical School.</p>
      </block>
